  "full_response": "Let  \n\n\u2003X_i = 1\u2003iff the random seat number r_i is in the k-long arc  \n\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003{j , j+1 , \u2026 , (j+k-1) (mod N)},  \n\n\u2003X_i = 0\u2003otherwise\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003(1)\n\nfor each of the n guests.  \nBecause r_i is chosen uniformly from N = 2n seats,\n\n\u2003Pr[X_i = 1] = k / N = k /(2n).                        \u2003\u2003(2)\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n1.  Distribution of X = \u03a3_{i=1}^{n} X_i\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\nThe variables X_1,\u2026,X_n are independent 0-1 variables, so\n\n\u2003X \u223c Binomial(n , p)\u2003with\u2003p = k/(2n).                   \u2003(3)\n\nIts expectation is\n\n\u2003\u03bc = E[X] = n\u00b7p = n\u00b7k/(2n) = k/2.                        \u2003(4)\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n2.  The event E_{j,k}\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\nE_{j,k} is the event that at least k of the r_i\u2019s fall in the arc, i.e.  \nE_{j,k} = { X \u2265 k }.\n\nNote that k = 2\u03bc, i.e. the event asks for twice the mean.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n3.  Chernoff bound\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\nFor any \u03b4 \u2265 0, a standard multiplicative Chernoff bound gives\n\n\u2003Pr[X \u2265 (1+\u03b4)\u03bc] \u2264 ( e^{\u03b4} / (1+\u03b4)^{1+\u03b4} )^{\u03bc}.             (5)\n\nTake \u03b4 = 1 (since (1+\u03b4)\u03bc = 2\u03bc = k):\n\n\u2003Pr[E_{j,k}] = Pr[X \u2265 k]  \n\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003 \u2264 ( e^{1} / 2^{2} )^{\u03bc}  \n\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003 = ( e / 4 )^{k/2}.                             (6)\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n4.  Converting to the required form\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\nLet  \n\n\u2003c = \u221a(4/e) = (4/e)^{1/2} \u2248 1.213 > 1,\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003\u2003(7)\n\na positive constant independent of n, N, and k.  \nThen (6) can be rewritten as\n\n\u2003Pr[E_{j,k}] \u2264 (e/4)^{k/2} = 1 / ( (4/e)^{k/2} ) = 1 / c^{\\,k}. (8)\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\n5.  Conclusion\n--------------------------------------------------------------------\nFor every arc of k consecutive seats and for every k \u2265 1,\n\n\u2003Pr[E_{j,k}] \u2264 1 / c^{\\,k}\u2003with\u2003c = \u221a(4/e) > 1,          (9)\n\nas required. \u220e\n\n\n\n\\boxed{\\text{Pr}[E_{j,k}] \\;\\le\\; c^{-k}\\ \\text{ for } c=\\sqrt{4/e}>1}  \n\nConfidence: 83%",
